Author: (Renier, 1804)
Common.Name: slime-tube feather-duster
Notes: Dr. Leslie Harris, polychaete expert, remarks: "different NEP websites & publications report this soft-sediment worm as both M. infundibulum & M. aesthetica, which is the first part of the confusion. In Europe M. infundibulum is found in soft-sediments & M. aesthetica is the one hanging from docks & hard-surfaces so if our NEP specimens are really the same as a European species they would be M. infundibulum. However, our NEP specimens are distinctly different both morphologically & genetically from infundibulum. The second part of the confusion is what to call them. In the past several NEP species of Myxicola were described from California, Puget Sound, & Alaska. All of the original specimens need to be re-examined so we can decide what name (or names) to use in the NEP."
